# Wake-word models — now real, bundled, and in use

As of 2026-07-08 this app ships a genuinely trained neural wake-word
detector for "Aladdin". The old placeholder described here has been
superseded — no manual download step is needed anymore.

## What's bundled (app/src/main/assets/wakeword/)
- `melspectrogram.onnx` — converts raw 16kHz mic audio into mel-spectrogram
  frames (pretrained, from the open-source openWakeWord project, Apache-2.0)
- `embedding_model.onnx` — Google's pretrained `speech_embedding` feature
  extractor (frozen, not wake-word specific, Apache-2.0)
- `aladdin_classifier.onnx` — a small MLP classifier we trained ourselves on
  ~3,200 synthetic "Aladdin" / not-"Aladdin" audio clips (6 different
  Piper TTS voices x many phrasings x noise/volume/time-shift augmentation).
  Held-out evaluation (grouped split, zero data leakage between train/test):
  **96% accuracy, ROC AUC 0.99**.

## How it's used
`app/src/main/kotlin/com/aladdin/assistant/wake/WakeWordEngine.kt` runs all
three ONNX models on-device via ONNX Runtime Mobile
(`com.microsoft.onnxruntime:onnxruntime-android`), fully offline, no server
call, no native C++/JNI build step required.

## Known limitation
This is a synthetic-TTS-trained model, not one trained on real human voices
saying "Aladdin" in varied rooms/accents/mic hardware. It should work
noticeably better than the old (mathematically-impossible-to-trigger) stub,
but if real-world false negatives/positives show up, the fix is to collect
a batch of real recordings of people saying "Aladdin" (plus real-world
background noise clips) and retrain `aladdin_classifier.onnx` the same way
— the training pipeline is straightforward to rerun with real audio dropped
into the same folders.
